DLC1 inhibits autophagy by decreasing T-cell factor 4 (TCF4) expression as well as -catenin and TCF4 interaction to inactivate Wnt/-catenin signaling and by suppressing the activity of ROCK1 and the Beclin1-Bcl2 complex dissociation in HCC cell lines, thereby decreasing autophagic activity.

description: DnaJ heat shock protein family (Hsp40) member B1
comment: DNAJB1 is involved in CMA (Chaperone-mediated autophagy). The authors found that Sirt1 promotes CMA activity by upregulating DNAJB1 expression and inhibiting astrocyte activation after CHI (Closed head injury). Sirt1 overexpression leads to deacetylation and ubiquitination modifications of DNAJB1, which helps to increase CMA activity and reduce neural loss.

description: DnaJ heat shock protein family (Hsp40) member B9
comment: DNAJB9 was found to be associated with autophagy. DNAJB9 is a small heat shock protein that can be activated by the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress response and promote autophagy for regulating protein demethylation. This may be because proteins that are demethylated, such as UFL1 , USP14 , and FADD, may be more easily regulated by autophagy feedback control.

description: ER degradation enhancing alpha-mannosidase like protein 1
comment: Through the study of Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) in neuronal cells, it was found that during virus replication, the virus replication complex colocalizes with EDEM1, an ERAD regulator. The ERAD structure required for virus replication is called EDEMosomes, and the virus replication complex colocalizes with both EDEMosomes and LC3-I labeled structures. The inhibition of autophagy leads to an increase of virus replication, while inhibition of EDEM1 and SEL1L can inhibit virus replication.

Blocking autophagy by genetically ablating or disrupting its function in ERBB2-enriched breast cancer virtually abolishes mammary tumorigenesis in the ERBB2-driven model, establishing that the effect is due to the loss of RB1CC1's autophagy function. This provides a new mechanism for autophagy to promote tumorigenesis in ERBB2-driven breast cancer by perturbing ERBB2 intracellular trafficking and triggering its release via small extracellular vesicles. Blocking autophagy can also control the trafficking of MVBs subtype to preferentially fuse with plasma membrane rather than lysosomes, leading to reduced ERBB2 expression.

When validating differentially expressed Autophagy genes, ERO1L was confirmed to be a gene with expression changes in two different genomic datasets. Overall, this paper demonstrates the correlation between ERO1L and Autophagy in ischemic stroke.

According to document the RNA expression levels of FKBP1B did not change in human iPSC-derived isogenic model. SAFIT2 can reduce HTT levels by modulating the autophagy degradation pathway, which suggests that FKBP1B may not be directly related to the autophagy pathway.

description: Fos proto-oncogene, AP-1 transcription factor subunit
comment: FOS is linked to autophagy through the transcriptional regulation of the BECN1/Beclin 1 gene. The experimental results found that the dopamine D2 and D3 receptor agonists pramipexole and quinpirole can enhance the transcriptional level of BECN1, thus promoting the initiation of autophagy. When the FOS gene is specifically interfered with, PPX cannot up-regulate LC3B-II and BECN1 or down-regulate SQSTM1. This indicates that the up-regulation of FOS is closely related to PPX-induced BECN1 transcriptional regulation and autophagy initiation.

GABARAP is highlighted as one of the protein families related to autophagy. These family members play a critical role in the autophagy process, such as promoting, garbage recognition, vesicle closure, and trafficking. The article lists several selective autophagy processes for specific substances, such as mitophagy, lipophagy, and xenophagy. In these selective autophagy processes, the LC3/GABARAP protein family plays an important role by binding to autophagy adaptor proteins.

description: heat shock protein 90 alpha family class B member 1
comment: HSP90AB1 is involved in Autophagy through inhibition of the AKT-MTOR pathway. It is mentioned that the pathogen receptor HSP90AB1, upon binding with avibirnavirus VP2, induces autophagy by inactivating the AKT-MTOR pathway.

description: inhibitor of nuclear factor kappa B kinase subunit epsilon
comment: IKBKE was identified as a positive regulator of autophagy. The study results showed that IKBKE could co-regulate autophagy and promote tumor cell proliferation in MDA-MB-231 and MDA-MB-468 triple-negative breast cancer cell lines.

SADS-CoV triggers Autophagy through the Akt/mTOR pathway to promote its own replication, and inhibition of Autophagy impedes viral replication. ITGA3 was found to inhibit the expression of the virus N protein and Autophagy induction. Under SADS-CoV infection, ITGA3 was found to regulate the Akt/mTOR pathway to induce Autophagy. In addition, the knockdown of ITGA3 leads to upregulation of Autophagy and increased replication of SADS-CoV.

ITGA6 expression is elevated in multiple cancers, including pancreatic cancer, and is associated with the tumor immune microenvironment and drug sensitivity. The risk score model used in the paper also includes ITGA6 as a key autophagy regulator.

ITGB1 was found to be an important factor regulating HULC-induced metastasis and invasion of ovarian cancer and was also identified as a key factor influencing autophagy, as reducing ITGB1 expression can promote cell autophagy and reduce tumor growth.

KIF5B is related to Autophagy because KIF5B has been found to drive tubulation of lysosomes. It is shown that KIF5B is capable of binding with PtdIns(4,5)P2 and can form tubules in liposomes that contain PtdIns(4,5)P2. Calthrin can also promote tubulation of autolysosomes and liposomes containing PtdIns(4,5)P2 in vitro. During autophagy, KIF5B clusters on PtdIns(4,5)P2-enriched microdomains which are essential for the recruitment and clustering of KIF5B. These findings suggest a motor-based membrane deformation process that is important in lysosomal homeostasis.

KLHL24 is shown to be a known autophagy-related mRNA that has been proven to be a validated target of an established autophagy related microRNA (miR 124), and is one of the mRNAs regulated by autophagy-inducing stimuli such as rapamycin and serum starvation in cancer cells. In this study, the authors found that KLHL24 is an mRNA related to breast cancer prognosis. Higher expression levels of KLHL24 are associated with better relapse-free survival in all breast cancer patients and ER+ only patients. KLHL24 mRNA levels can be used as a biomarker to monitor autophagy in breast cancer patients.

MAPK1 and MAPK14 signaling pathways and their activity are essential for mitophagy induced by hypoxia and starvation conditions. The activity of MAPK1 and MAPK14 is enhanced under these two conditions. Previous studies have described the way mitochondria undergo autophagy in the PINK1-PARK2 signaling pathway, but the results of this paper suggest that in mammalian cells, the alternative autophagy pathway that is apparently different from conventional autophagy (participated by MAPK1 and MAPK14) is the primary way of mitophagy.

MAPK8IP1 is a key regulator of autophagosome transport in neurons. MAPK8IP1 directly regulates the dynamic behavior of autophagosomes by binding to motor proteins and actin. It also inhibits the binding of KIF5 and autophagosomes by binding to LC3 to ensure the unidirectional retrograde transport of autophagosomes. Furthermore, researchers found that the phosphorylation state of MAPK8IP1 affects the direction of autophagosome transport. When MAPK8IP1 is in an unphosphorylated state, retrograde autophagosome transport occurs.

MAPK9 promoted stress-induced mitophagy by promoting ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation of small mitochondrial ARF (smARF) and inducing excessive autophagy. smARF is a short isoform of the tumor suppressor ARF produced by alternative translational initiation at Met45 and localizes exclusively to mitochondria. Loss of MAPK9 led to the accumulation of smARF, which induced excessive autophagy that resulted in lysosomal degradation of the mitophagy adaptor p62 at steady-state. Depletion of p62 prevented MAPK9-deficient cells from mounting mitophagy upon stress and MAPK9-deficient mice displayed defective mitophagy, which caused tissue damage under hypoxic stress, hyperactivation of inflammasomes, and increased mortality in sepsis.

description: membrane bound transcription factor peptidase, site 2
comment: Through RT-qPCR, the experimental results showed that the expression level of MBTPS2 in tumor samples was relatively low. The experimental results also confirmed that MYC and MBTPS2 were related to autophagy and osteosarcoma cell metastasis. Through MYC silencing and MBTPS2 overexpression, the researchers found that autophagy in tumor cells was suppressed.

MTMR14 plays an important role in regulating autophagy as a type of myotubularin protein. The modification of PIs is an important mechanism for controlling organelle and membrane traffic, and they also play an important role in the regulation of autophagy. The study explored the correlation between MTMR14 and autophagy dysregulation through double knockdown of MTMR14, which could explain certain pathological conditions such as centronuclear myopathy. The authors also discuss the function of MTMR14 as a modifier of disease severity, rather than a primary cause.

NCKAP1 is related to autophagy by binding to two autophagy receptors, NDP52 and TAX1BP1, to recruit TBK1 and mediate the efficiency of xenophagy and mitophagy. Recent research indicates that the recruitment of TBK1 to NDP52 and TAX1BP1 via NCKAP1 is required for efficient xenophagy and mitophagy.
NFKB1 promotes the expression of GFRA1 by binding to the promoter region of the GFRA1 gene. GFRA1 induces autophagy through the SRC-AMPK signaling pathway.

NKX2-3 is related to autophagy by inducing autophagy through the AMPK/mTOR signaling pathway, thus inhibiting the proliferation and migration of VSMCs. The experimental results show that NKX2-3 can inhibit the proliferation and migration of VSMCs by enhancing their autophagy.

NRG1 inhibits autophagy through the Akt/mTOR signaling pathway to alleviate sepsis-induced skeletal muscle atrophy. Exogenous addition of NRG1 in septic cell models can inhibit autophagy and increase cell viability by activating the Akt/mTOR signaling pathway. In the SD rat model, intravenous injection of NRG1 can also inhibit autophagy, promote weight gain in rats and alleviate atrophy in the tibialis anterior muscle.

NRG2 is related to autophagy in that NRG2 can stimulate LNCaP cells to undergo autophagic cell death, meaning that NRG2 induces cell death in LNCaP cells . At the same time, the NRG2-induced cell death is also thought to be related to the PI3K pathway and PI3K inhibitors can inhibit NRG2-induced cell death.

NRG3 is one of the 5 Autophagy-related genes used to establish an assessment index that predicts the therapy efficacy of endometrial cancer (EC). NRG3 is related to the ERBB family signaling pathway, which can affect Autophagy through the pathway.

P4HB is related to autophagy, as it may interact with endoplasmic reticulum stress-related proteins (such as HSP90B1, HSPA5 and PDIA6), thereby participating in the autophagy process in renal tumor cells.

PARP1, the founding member of the PARP family, has functions in DNA repair, replication, genome integrity, cell cycle, and metabolism, and it is able to maintain cell homeostasis. PARP1 activation and PARylation play critical roles in maintaining the autophagy pathway.

PEA15 is an Autophagy-promoting protein that induces TGF-beta's Autophagy in L6 and C2C12 cells through a PP2A/FoxO1-mediated mechanism. This impairs differentiation into mature muscle cells. TGF-beta transcriptionally upregulates the Autophagy-promoting gene PEA15, which in turn induces atrophic responses in skeletal muscle.

description: proline, glutamate and leucine rich protein 1
comment: PELP1 is recruited into autophagosomes to respond to autophagy. This process may be due to the interaction between HRS and PELP1, as HRS and PELP1 appear together in autophagosomes according to the results . Further experiments suggest that the degradation of PELP1 may be achieved through autophagy.

PEX14 is the only essential component of the peroxisomal translocon required for pexophagy, responsible for the recognition and subsequent sequestration of a single peroxisome by multiple membrane layers, leading to degradation of the entire organelle by vacuolar enzymes. Additionally, PEX14 has a dual function in peroxisome formation and selective degradation.

PEX3 is a protein that is important for PEXOPHAGY (a type of selective autophagy in which peroxisomes are sequestered in an RPC for lysosomal degradation). It works together with ATG30 in constructing PEXOPHAGIC RPC (receptor-protein complex). The study demonstrated that ATG30 requires ATG37 and PEX3 to recruit ATG8 and ATG11 to the PEXOPHAGIC RPC, and that the proper localization of PEX3 depends on ATG37.
PIK3R4  helps in the initiation and progression of autophagy by producing PtdIns3P.

PPP1R15A is related to autophagy because PPP1R15A is a component of the PP1 phosphatase complex, which can reverse the inhibitory effect of protein synthesis by dephosphorylating eIF2. In addition, this study found that PPP1R15A regulates translation levels during starvation and promotes autophagy. The absence of PPP1R15A leads to excessive phosphorylation of eIF2 and a reduction in subsequent steps of autophagy.

description: protein kinase cAMP-dependent type I regulatory subunit alpha
comment: PRKAR1A is related to Autophagy by spatial and functional interaction with mTOR kinase, participating in the process of Autophagosome maturation. RIa localizes on LC3-positive Autophagosomal membranes and recruits mTOR kinase to inhibit its activity, thus promoting Autophagosome maturation. Additionally, the paper mentions that PRKAR1A depletion leads to Autophagy deficiency, and the accumulation of Lipofuscin-like material in the cells and tissues of CNC and PPNAD patients is a hallmark of Autophagy deficiency. Therefore, the RIa-mTOR complex plays a crucial role in the regulation of mammalian Autophagy, and PRKAR1A depletion leads to Autophagy deficiency.

PTK6 promotes the proliferation, migration, and invasion of uveal melanoma cells by inhibiting Autophagy. Meanwhile, PTK6 can bind to SOCS3 and upregulate the phosphorylation of mechanistic target of rapamycin (mTOR) to further inhibit Autophagy. Therefore, this article provides a new molecular mechanism of PTK6 in Autophagy dysfunction-mediated uveal melanoma.

RAB24 is localized to the endoplasmic reticulum inside cells and is thought to primarily participate in autophagosome maturation. Under normal conditions, RAB24 presents a reticular distribution around the nucleus. In contrast, in amino acid starvation-induced autophagy, the distribution of RAB24 changes into punctate spots, larger dots, ring-shaped small vesicles, and some tubular-like structures, and these structures colocalize with markers for autophagic vacuoles, such as LC3 and monodansylcadaverine. The overexpression of wt RAB24 caused an increase in autophagosomes, whereas in cells overexpressing the mutant RAB24S67L, the amount of autophagosomes decreased. These results demonstrated for the first time that RAB24 is involved in autophagy.

RAB33B is involved in both autophagic processes and membrane trafficking. In the process of autophagy, RAB33B plays a role in autophagosome formation and maturation. Meanwhile, RAB33B is also involved in the transport of various substances such as cargo movement, tethering, and fusion operating between different endomembrane compartments of the cell.

RAB5A is a direct target gene in the CLEAR network regulated by TFEB. Under TGF- induction, TFEB-driven autophagy can regulate the endocytosis of Itg51 and promote the progression of pancreatic cancer cells.  In addition, RAB5A is also an important regulatory protein of endocytosis, playing a critical role in many tumors.

RAC1 is an important regulator of cytoskeletal reorganization, gene expression, cell morphology, cell motility, and activation of the NADPH oxidase complex. The document suggests that RAC1 is one of the important regulators of autophagy and has been associated with sarcoidosis. In addition, the role of RAC1 in autophagy process is also discussed in the document. In various diseases, cell death is associated with the activation state of RAC1. Autophagy plays an important role in maintaining cellular metabolic homeostasis, cell survival, and regulating lactate-internal lipid deposition in the class organelles.

RAF1 is a crucial component of the EGFR (Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor) signaling pathway. In this paper, a novel autophagy enhancer called w09 was studied, which induced cell autophagy and apoptosis by activating the EGFR-mediated RAS-RAF1-MAP2K-MAPK1/3 signaling pathway. Inhibition of the RAS-RAF1-MAP2K-MAPK1/3 pathway with U0126 or blockade of autophagy attenuated the effects of w09, suggesting that w09 induces autophagy through the RAS-RAF1-MAP2K-MAPK1/3 signaling pathway. Therefore, RAF1 plays a critical role in the process of w09-induced autophagy.

SAR1A knockdown can induce ER stress, ROS generation, and increased autophagic activity, leading to reduced migratory and invasive ability of osteosarcoma cells. LC3I to LC3II conversion and P62 levels were decreased, which are hallmarks of autophagic activity. Additionally, SAR1A knockdown can downregulate the expression of RhoA and inhibit osteosarcoma metastasis, possibly related to ROS accumulation, increased autophagic activity, and the influence of the RhoA/YAP signaling pathway. Therefore, SAR1A can regulate osteosarcoma metastasis and invasion by affecting cell autophagic activity.

SPNS1 is associated with the autophagy system through its involvement in lysosomal acidification and the fusion process between autophagosome and lysosome. In addition, the study found that there is an interaction between SPNS1 and v-ATPase, and both regulate the aging process of cells during development and the acidification state of autolysosomes.

TM9SF1 was found to be a gene that promotes the formation of autophagosomes. Its overexpression can significantly increase the number of GFP-LC3 dots in cells, which was confirmed by transmission electron microscopy and immunoblotting. In contrast, inhibiting the expression of TM9SF1 by RNA interference can hinder cell autophagy.

VAMP3 is associated with autophagy by forming a complex with STX6 and VTI1B to regulate the fusion of recycling endosomes with autophagosomes, thereby promoting pathogen degradation. The study suggests that VAMP3 and VTI1B function together with STX6 to regulate the RE-GcAV fusion step, and their contribution facilitates GcAV formation to restrict bacterial proliferation in cells.

VAMP7A is related to autophagy by participating in the fusion process between autophagosomes and lysosomes together with STX17. VAMP7B, produced by alternative splicing, can compete with VAMP7A to bind with STX17, inhibiting the realization of cellular autophagy.

VAMP7A is related to autophagy by participating in the fusion process between autophagosomes and lysosomes together with STX17. VAMP7B, produced by alternative splicing, can compete with VAMP7A to bind with STX17, inhibiting the realization of cellular autophagy.

The study found that autophagy induces the expression of VEGFA in human lung cancer cells, and blocking autophagy enhances the cytotoxic and anti-angiogenic effects of anlotinib through the JAK2/STAT3/VEGFA pathway. Additionally, co-administration of anlotinib and chloroquine further reduces VEGFA levels in tumour cells.
WDR45B is related to autophagy by its striking similarities with previously studied Vmp1 mutants. This suggests that WDR45B also regulates the same autophagosome formation pathway.

WIPI1 is related to autophagy by promoting the fission of endosomal transport carriers and formation of autophagosomes through distinct mechanisms. WIPI1 participates in the formation and fission of vesicular endosomal transport carriers, supporting PtdIns(3,5)P2-dependent transport of endosomal cargo towards the plasma membrane, Golgi, and lysosomes.

P53 directly regulates the transcription of ACER2, significantly stimulating ACER2 expression, and ACER2-mediated autophagy and apoptosis are found to be connected with ROS generation. The interaction of ACER2 with autophagy drives its impact on apoptosis. ACER2 induces autophagy and apoptosis through the production of ROS.

ADRB2 negatively regulated autophagy to promote the progression of HCC. The ADRB2 signaling pathway inhibited autophagy by increasing Akt-dependent beclin1 homodimer formation, resulting in the stabilization of HIF1 and metabolic reprogramming. In addition, blocking ADRB2 signaling enhanced Sorafenib-induced autophagy and improved the anti-tumor effects of Sorafenib.
ATF6 is essential for the successful execution of bacterial infections and IFN-induced autophagy.
ATG101 has a HORMA structure similar to Atg13 and its main role is to recruit downstream factors to the Autophagy formation site and participate in Autophagy via a region called the "WF finger".

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit a1
comment: Knockdown of ATP6V0A1 can strengthen the aggregation of autophagosomes and increase GMI-induced autophagic cell death.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit a2
comment: PHY34 induces autophagy inhibition and tumor cell apoptosis in ovarian cancer cells by inhibiting the ATP6V0A2 subunit localization of proteins.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit b
comment: ATP6V0B is a lysosomal proton pump protein that plays a critical role in the formation and maintenance of the endolysosomal system and is an essential component of autophagy.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit c
comment: ATP6V0C in promoting selective autophagy and the mechanism of its interaction with SopF.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit d1
comment: ATP6V0D1 is a key protein in autophagy-related molecular networks in many CNS disorders.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit d2
comment: ATP6V0D2 is a subunit of the H+-ATPase proton pump and an important component of autophagosomes and osteoclasts.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit e1
comment: ATP6V0E1 plays an important role in both lysosomal function and the autophagic process.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V0 subunit e2
comment: ATP6V0E2 is a protein that is responsible for acidification inside the cell, and it also plays a role in adjusting acidity in lysosomes. Autophagy is a way for cells to clear waste, and it is critical for the formation of foam cells. The increased expression of ATG5 and P62 reflects the decrease in autophagic flux, which may be caused by the downregulation of ATP6V0E2 expression.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit A
comment: ATP6V1A subunit of the lysosomal v-ATPase, a protein complex that regulates mTORC1.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit B1
comment: Although ATP6V1B1 is not mentioned, the V-ATPase complex it is part of plays a crucial role in lysosomal function and ALP.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit B2
comment: ATP6V1B2 mutations are associated with the activation of autophagy and the maintenance of mTOR/TOR state,?ATP6V1B2 mutations can also promote pyroptosis.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit C1
comment: ATP6V1C1 enhances resistance to radiotherapy-induced death, and promotes Autophagy through the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit C2
comment: ATP6V1C2 encodes vacuolar-H+ ATPase (V-ATPase), which is essential for lysosome/vacuole acidification and affects cellular processes such as endocytosis, vacuole fusion, and protein degradation. Additionally, ATP6V1C2 modulates the concentration of neurotransmitters into synaptic vesicles and is crucial in synaptic transmission.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit D
comment: ATP6V1D is one of the active V-ATPase subunits involved in lysosomal acidification,  related to the role of lysosome in autophagy.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit E1
comment: ATP6V1E1 is related to Autophagy through the Autophagy-related gene Atg5.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit G1
comment: Oxidized stress-induced ATM activation phosphorylates ATP6V1G1, maintaining lysosomal acidification to facilitate the fusion of autophagosomes.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit G2
comment: ATP6V1G2 is an ATPase subunit involved in the acidification process of lysosomes, and thus involved in autophagy in cells. Treatment with -Cypermethrin led to overexpression of the ATP6V1G2 gene, indicating changes in the cell autophagy pathway caused by this insecticide.

description: ATPase H+ transporting V1 subunit H
comment: ATP6V1H can be regulated by CREG1,CREG1 can promote the formation and maintenance of lysosomal function, thus accelerating the process of autophagy.

description: AUP1 lipid droplet regulating VLDL assembly factor
comment: AUP1 is related to Autophagy mainly because of its interaction with autophagy-related proteins HMGB and YWHA/14-3-3 proteins on LDs. AUP1 is also regarded as a key factor in aggrephagy-like mechanism via promoting the formation of aggresome to facilitate lipophagy and cholesterol efflux.
CAMKK2 phosphorylates AMPK and promotes autophagy.
The complex of CDC37 and HSP90 can regulate Ulk1- and Atg13-mediated autophagy in cells and the disintegration of CDC37/HSP90 complex triggers an autophagic clearance cascade for TDP-43 protein.
S-nitrosylation inhibits CDK5 S-sulfenylation and reduces its kinase activity, leading to attenuation of CDK5-mediated autophagy and MPTP-induced neurotoxicity.
CDK5R1 activity following starvation appears to be required for starvation-induced autophagy.
CLEC16A gene is autophagy, which affects TEC antigen presentation and subsequently impacts T cell selection and reactivity.
CLU protein can also be released from the endoplasmic reticulum/Golgi to the cytosol where it forms complexes and traffics them for degradation via Autophagy and/or proteasome.

CPTP regulates autophagy and inflammasome activation, through the trafficking of C1P from the trans-Golgi to target membranes. Downregulation of CPTP leads to an increase in autophagosomes and altered levels of endogenous proteins. Moreover, CPTP knockdown-induced autophagy elevates early markers of autophagosome formation and suppresses MTOR phosphorylation.
Previous research has shown that overexpression of CK2 enhances DISC activity, thereby promoting TRAIL-induced apoptosis in human colon carcinoma cell lines.

CTSA regulates the activity of CMA by degrading LAMP-2A. CMA is a form of autophagy involved in the degradation of cytoplasmic proteins, participating in the regulation of hepatic lipid and carbohydrate metabolism. This study found that SNX10 deficiency increased the stability of LAMP-2A, activating the CMA activity to alleviate alcohol-induced liver injury and steatosis. SNX10 controls CMA activity by regulating CTSA maturation.
CTTN regulates the stability of actin filaments to promote fusion of autophagosomes with lysosomes in Autophagy.

DDRGK1 plays an important role in regulating autophagy by controlling lysosomal function. The study shows that deficiency of DDRGK1 leads to a dual effect on autophagy, resulting in the accumulation of autophagosomes and the inhibition of autophagosome-lysosome fusion, ultimately leading to apoptosis. The study also reveals that DDRGK1 loss leads to impaired lysosomal function, including aberrant lysosomal pH, Cathepsin D (CTSD) expression, and v-ATPase accumulation, thereby compromising the autophagy process.

description: DEP domain containing 5, GATOR1 subcomplex subunit
comment: DEPDC5 led to constitutive hyperactivation of MTORC1, resulting in early-onset myopathy and cardiac dysfunction associated with oxidative damage and accumulation of SQSTM1/p62.
DEPP was found to induce autophagy in neuroblastoma cells and to mediate the formation of autophagosomes by increasing reactive oxygen species levels.
DHRSX encodes an atypical secretory protein that can promote hunger induced autophagy.
DHRSX encodes an atypical secretory protein that can promote hunger induced autophagy.
Targeting EEF1A1 using specific molecules resulted in the activation of autophagy in MEC-1, a prototype cell line of CLL.
PE modification of EEF1A2 protein can insert into lipid monolayers, which is similar to the modification of LC3 protein and is also related to Autophagy.

description: eukaryotic translation initiation factor 2 alpha kinase 4
comment: EIF2AK4-EIF2A/eIF2a-ATF4 pathway triggers an autophagic response of intestinal epithelial cells to Crohn's disease associated invasive Escherichia coli (AIEC) infection.

description: endosome-lysosome associated apoptosis and autophagy regulator 1
comment: ELAPOR1 is localized in late endosomes and lysosomes within cells, which are key areas of autophagy.
EXOC1 is an effector of RalB and is responsible for regulating autophagosome formation during cellular starvation.
BECN1 can form a complex with EXOC4/SEC8, which promotes the secretion of adiponectin, C1Q and collagen domain containing and improves energy metabolism and insulin sensitivity.

EXOC7 is a member of the human exocyst complex, which is composed of proteins encoded by eight genes and is associated with autophagy. As the generation of exosomes depends on the involvement of the autophagy pathway, these processes can sometimes be mutually constraining.

description: F-box and WD repeat domain containing 7
comment: FBXW7 overexpression significantly promoted the formation of the ATG12-ATG5-ATG16L1 protein complex and markedly enhanced the conversion of LC3-I to LC3-II induced by oxaliplatin in hepatic stellate cells. Additionally, the GFP-LC3 puncta formation assay and transmission electron microscopy demonstrated that FBXW7 enhanced autophagy in hepatic stellate cells.

The experiment found that FEZ1 inhibits autophagy during starvation by interacting with Golgi-located SCOC. At the same time, knockdown of FEZ1 and FEZ2 or overexpression of both can increase the activity of autophagy

Similar to FEZ1, this study shows that FEZ2 inhibits autophagy during starvation by binding with the protein SCOC. The study also shows that FEZ2 and RAB3GAP1/2 can reciprocally regulate the autophagic process, and serve as novel conserved factors of the autophagy and proteostasis network.

FOXK1 suppresses autophagy by inhibiting the expression of autophagy-related genes. DNA damage induces CHK2 to phosphorylate FOXK1, and creates a binding site between FOXK1 and 14-3-3_, thus trapping FOXK1 in the cytoplasm. This relieves the inhibition on the expression of autophagy-related genes and promotes autophagy.

DNA damage induces CHK2-mediated FOXK phosphorylation, which confines FOXK to the cytoplasm, relieves its inhibition on the expression of autophagy-related genes, and facilitates autophagy. In addition, a significant increase in autophagy has been demonstrated in cells by reducing the expression of FOXK2.
FTH1 is regulated by autophagy, which leads to high levels of iron ions that induce iron-dependent lipid peroxidation, ultimately resulting in cell death.

By interfering with FTL activity, ADI inhibits the protein that stores iron in the cytosol while activating the mitochondrial apoptosis pathway. When arginine is deficient, the process of chromatin autophagy appears at a later stage, stimulating cancer cells to use histone arginine and accelerating cancer cell death.

description: FYVE and coiled-coil domain autophagy adaptor 1
comment: FYCO1 is a FYVE zinc finger domain adaptor protein that plays a role in microtubule-dependent, plus-end-directed transport of autophagic vesicles, delivering autophagosomes to the lysosomes for degradation. Loss of FYCO1 function can lead to the development of cataracts, and the FYCO1-dependent autophagy pathway is critical for lens morphogenesis.
GAPDH (GAPC in plants) interacts with phosphatidic acid and inhibits autophagy. It competes with the autophagy-related protein ATG3 for binding to phosphatidic acid at the same binding interface.

The enzyme encoded by GBA1, glucocerebrosidase is an important degradative enzyme in lysosomes and contributes to the degradation of alpha-synuclein. Mutations in LRRK2 and GBA1 related to Parkinson's disease slow the degradation of alpha-synuclein.
AxD mutant GFAP accumulation stimulates autophagy.
GPR137B as a member of the lysosomal regulatory complex, affecting the activity and localization of mTORC1 kinase.
GPSM1 is one of the inhibitors of Gi3, which is related to the autophagy signaling pathway.
GSK3A hinders the autophagy process of clearing cell debris and increases the expression of the cellular senescence marker.

HAX1 promotes cell survival by mitigating damaged signals from endoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria. Upon oxidative stress, enhanced autophagy induction was observed in cells overexpressing HAX1 and HAX1 truncations, which leads to a suppression of mitochondrial membrane potential dissipation and apoptosis. The study also identified amino acids 127-180 in HAX1 as the functional autophagy-regulatory domain, responsible for the autophagic induction.

HGF participates in Autophagy through the activation of MET activity. The HGF-MET signaling pathway inhibits the expression of cell cycle regulatory proteins p27kip-1 and p21cip-1, thereby enhancing the process of autophagy. The study found that the HGF-MET signal can activate autophagy through the Stathmin and COPII pathways.

description: heat shock protein family B (small) member 1
comment: Mutations in HSPB1 impair macroautophagy/autophagy flux, leading to a decrease in the formation of SQSTM1/p62 bodies, and subsequent impairment of phagophore formation. The wild-type HSPB1 protein binds to the autophagy receptor SQSTM1/p62 and this interaction is disturbed by mutations in HSPB1. The impairment of autophagy might be one of the pathomechanisms by which mutations in HSPB1 lead to peripheral neuropathy.

IL4 induces autophagy in B cells, leading to sustained cell survival and antigen presentation, and ultimately exacerbating asthma symptoms. The JAK signaling pathway promotes IL4-induced autophagy, and that IL4 promotes the formation and activation of the autophagy-specific PtdIns3K complex, which is essential for the nucleation, elongation, and formation of autophagosomes in B cells. This complex is composed of BECN1, PIK3R4, PIK3C3, and ATG14, and is responsible for recruiting essential ATG proteins to the phagophore assembly sites.

KEAP1 is related to autophagy through the p62/Keap1/Nrf2 system. p62 activates the antioxidant transcription factor Nrf2 by a non-canonical pathway, which is completely independent of the redox state, and involves the recruitment of Keap1 associated with the Cul3-ubiquitin E3 ligase complex responsible for degrading Nrf2. When phosphorylated at Ser351, p62 binds to aggregates of ubiquitylated proteins and increases its affinity for Keap1. This event induces Keap1 degradation via autophagy, leaving Nrf2 free to accumulate and translocate in the nucleus. Nrf2 binds to the antioxidant-responsive elements (ARE) in the promoter regions of antioxidant and detoxifying genes.

description: late endosomal/lysosomal adaptor, MAPK and MTOR activator 5
comment: LAMTOR5 can directly interact with TLR4 and promote its localization in autophagosomes, thus promoting the autophagic degradation of TLR4. LAMTOR5 expression leads to the conversion of LC3-I to LC3-II and increased stability of p62 and reduces the activity of mTORC1, promoting the initiation of autophagy.

MIRLET7B regulates autophagy by downregulating autophagy-related genes. Under ROS stimulation, the expression of autophagy-related genes in MSCs will increase, but this phenomenon will be suppressed after MIRLET7B transfection.

The MTMR6/R9 complex can inhibit stress-induced apoptosis, whereas the MTMR8/R9 complex inhibits autophagy. Studies have shown that overexpression of MTMR8 and MTMR9 significantly increases the level of p62, while RNAi of both MTMR8 and MTMR9 significantly reduces the level of p62 in HeLa cells treated with 100 nM bafilomycin A1 for 3 hours. Unlike the upregulation of autophagy by the MTMR8/R9 complex, the inhibition of the MTMR8/R9 complex induces autophagy.

Increased ORMDL3 expression induces autophagy, resulting in impairing bronchial epithelial function in asthma by inhibiting intracellular calcium influx and inducing cell death. ORMDL3 is implicated in sphingolipid metabolism, the endoplasmic reticulum unfolded protein response, and concentration of intracellular calcium.

PJVK can initiate autophagy degradation of peroxisomes damaged by oxidative stress by recruiting LC3B. In addition, PJVK can also mediate the autophagy degradation of lipid droplets by directly binding with LC3B, thereby protecting auditory cells from oxidative stress damage. PJVK regulates the autophagy process under noise-induced oxidative stress damage, providing a theoretical basis for the prevention of autophagy-related auditory injury.

description: protein kinase AMP-activated non-catalytic subunit gamma 1
comment: PRKAG1 was found to be a positive regulator of autophagy through its interaction with PRKDC. Under normal conditions, PRKDC interacts with the AMPK complex and phosphorylates its nucleotide-sensing subunit, promoting lysosomal activation of the AMPK complex. PRKDC-mediated phosphorylation of PRKAG1 primes cells for lysosomal activation by STK11 in cancer cells.

The absence of RMC1 affects the steady-state and selective autophagy, and suppresses Autophagic flux. The study results indicate that RMC1 is an important cell membrane protein that participates in the process of intracellular waste removal. In particular, under normal conditions, Autophagic flux in cells is regulated by RMC1.
